{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Gatsby is a powerful platform for building marketing sites, blogs,\necommerce frontends, and more. You can source data from static files\nand any number of content management systems. You can process images,\nadd support for our favorite styling technique, transform markdown,\nand just about anything else you can imagine."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"At its core, a Gatsby site is a combination of functionality centered\naround a single config file, "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"gatsby-config.js"}]},{"type":"text","value":". This config file\ncontrols an assortment of site metadata, data type mapping, and most\nimportantly, plugins. Plugins contain large amounts of customizable\nfunctionality for turning markdown into pages, processing components\ninto documentation, and even processing images."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{"id":"scaling-gatsby"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"#scaling-gatsby","ariaLabel":"scaling gatsby permalink","className":["anchor"]},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"svg","properties":{"ariaHidden":"true","focusable":"false","height":"16","version":"1.1","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","width":"16"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"},"children":[]}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"Scaling Gatsby"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Creating a single Gatsby site works super well. The power of\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"gatsby-config.js"}]},{"type":"text","value":", plugins, and more coalesce to make the experience a\nbreeze. However, what if you want to re-use this configuration on our\nnext site? Sure, you could clone a boilerplate each time, but that gets\nold, quickly. Wouldn’t it be great if you could re-use our\ngatsby-config.js across projects? That’s where starters come in."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h3","properties":{"id":"improving-reusability-with-starters"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"#improving-reusability-with-starters","ariaLabel":"improving reusability with starters permalink","className":["anchor"]},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"svg","properties":{"ariaHidden":"true","focusable":"false","height":"16","version":"1.1","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","width":"16"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"},"children":[]}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"Improving Reusability with Starters"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"One way to create more sites with similar functionality faster is to\nuse starters. Starters are basically whole Gatsby sites that can be\nscaffolded through the gatsby CLI. This helps you start your project\nby cloning the boilerplate, installing dependencies, and clearing Git\nhistory. The community around Gatsby has built a lot of different\nstarters for various use cases including blogging, working with\nmaterial design, and documentation."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The problem with starters is that they’re one-offs. Starters are\nboilerplate projects that begin to diverge immediately from upstream\nand have no easy way of updating when changes are made\nupstream. There’s another approach to boilerplate that has become\npopular in recent years that fixes some problems with the boilerplate\napproach such as updating with upstream. One such project is\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://facebook.github.io/create-react-app/"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"create-react-app"}]}]},{"type":"text","value":". In\nthe Gatsby world, you can improve on starters similarly with themes."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h3","properties":{"id":"truly-reusable-themes-in-gatsby"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"#truly-reusable-themes-in-gatsby","ariaLabel":"truly reusable themes in gatsby permalink","className":["anchor"]},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"svg","properties":{"ariaHidden":"true","focusable":"false","height":"16","version":"1.1","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","width":"16"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"},"children":[]}]}]},{"type":"text","value":"Truly Reusable Themes in Gatsby"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If a single "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"gatsby-config.js"}]},{"type":"text","value":" encodes the functionality of a whole Gatsby\nsite, then if you can\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://medium.com/javascript-scene/master-the-javascript-interview-what-is-function-composition-20dfb109a1a0"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"compose"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\nthe "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"gatsby-config.js"}]},{"type":"text","value":" data structure together you have the base for\nthemes. You can encode portions of our gatsby-config as themes and\nre-use them across sites. This is a big deal because you can have a\ntheme config (or multiple configs) that composes together with the\ncustom config (for the current site). Upgrading the underlying theme\ndoes not undo the customizations, meaning you get upstream\nimprovements to the theme without a difficult manual upgrade process."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{"id":"why-themes"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"#why-themes","ariaLabel":"why themes permalink","className":["anchor"]},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"svg","properties":{"ariaHidden":"true","focusable":"false","height":"16","version":"1.1","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","width":"16"},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1